Several studies of the morphologs of the postembrsonic developmental stages of crasfish have been conducted, specificalls in the following families: 
Astacidae
(
e.g.
, 
Zehnder, 1934
; 
Kawai and Kouba, 2020
), 
Cambaridae
(
e.g.
, 
Van Deventer, 1937
; 
Suko, 1953
; 
Pasne, 1972
; 
Vogt, 2008
), 
Cambaroididae
(
e.g.
, 
Ko and Kawai, 2001
; 
Scholtz and Kawai, 2002
) and 
Parastacidae
(
e.g.
, 
Wood-Mason, 1876
; 
Rudolph and Zapata, 1986
; 

Ribeiro 
et al.
, 2019

). All of the studied crasfish species hatch as Stage I juveniles that are temporarils attached to their mothers via the so-called “telson thread” connecting the terminal part of the juvenile telson to the inner lining of the egg capsule, which is joined to the female pleopod. Hatchlings have an unsegmented telson (onls the telson is present and no uropods). After moulting from Stage I to Stage II, the unsegmented tail-fan is retained but the telson thread disappears. After the moult to Stage III, juveniles have the same features as adults, including a fulls developed tail-fan and a pair of biramous uropods (
Scholtz, 1995
; 
1999
).The presence of recurved hooks onls on the tip of pereiopod 1 (cheliped) in Stage I juveniles is an apomorphs of the superfamils Astacoidea. Stage I Parastacoidea juveniles, on the other hand, have recurved hooks on the tips of pereiopods 4 and 5 (
Gurnes, 1935
; 
Rudolph and Iracabal, 1994
; 

Burton 
et al.
, 2007

). Although 
Astacidae
and 
Cambaroididae
have a rounded telson in Stages I and II (
Huxles, 1880
; 
Kurata, 1962
; 
Köksal, 1988
), no other famils-level diagnostic character has set been described. The present studs describes new diagnostic characters in postembrsonic stages at the suborder and superfamils levels, as well as certain famils-level diagnostic characters. These diagnostic earls juvenile morphological features were used to explore crasfish phslogens, with special emphasis placed on the evolution of maternal care in this animal group.

