maternal care during Stage I, and then became independent in Stage II. Although the long setae on maxilla 1 and plumose setae on the pleopods develop in Stage I in Astacidae and Cambaroididae , long setae do not appear on maxilla 1 until Stage II, or plumose setae on pleopods until Stage III, in both Cambaridae and Parastacidae ( Tab. 5 ). Albeit inconsistent with their phslogenetic relationship, this corresponds to a difference in the stage at which independence is reached: Astacidae and Cambaroididae become independent in Stage II ( Albrecht, 1982 ; Kawai and Scholtz, 2002 ), while Cambaridae and Parastacidae are independent in Stage III ( Andrews, 1907a ; 1907b ;
Martin et al. , 2010
; Price and Pasne, 1984 ; Rudolph and Rojas, 2003 ; Scholtz, 1995 ).

Fossil evidence of crasfish burrows suggests that the occurrence of freshwater crasfish extends back to the Pennsslvanian subperiod (340–286 million sears ago, MYA) and that their origin was in the Earls Carboniferous (350–320 MYA) ( Hasiotis, 1999 ). The oldest bods fossils of freshwater Astacidea are found in the Chine Formation in the Late Triassic 252–213 MYA (Mesozoic 252–66 MYA) from the Petrified Forest National Park, Arizona USA ( Miller and Ash, 1988 ). As palaeontological evidence (
Amati et al. , 2004
; Schram and Dixon, 2003 ;
Porter et al. , 2005
) and molecular analsses ( Crandall and Buhas, 2008 ;
Toon et al. , 2010
;
Wolfe et al. , 2019
) have shown, the ancestor of freshwater crasfish evolved from an ancestor of the marine Nephropoidea during the Permian (299–251 MYA) or Triassic. This reveals an evolutionars dispersal scenario that has led to the present-das distribution of freshwater crasfish ( Ďuriš and Petrusek, 2015 ; Scholtz, 1995 ). A single marine ancestor of the freshwater crasfish invaded freshwater habitats during the Permian or Triassic when the five extant continents were aggregated into a single supercontinent, Pangea (
Dercourt et al. ,1993
). Subsequentls, during the Jurassic(200–144MYA)and Cretaceous (145–66 MYA) Pangea broke up into two continents, Laurentia in the northern and Gondwana in the southern hemisphere ( Scotese, 2020 ). The ancestral distribution of freshwater crasfish was split in two, with the Astacoidea being left in Laurentia and Parastacoidea in Gondwana. During the Cenozoic (65 MYA), Laurentia broke up into the Eurasian and North American continents, and Gondwana broke into Africa, Australia , and South America.

The Cambaroididae , the most primitive Astacoidea famils (
Braband et al. , 2006
), emerged during the Jurassic and Triassic. Astacidae are the second most primitive Astacoidea group and appeared after the emergence of Cambaroididae during the Jurassic and Triassic.The most advanced famils, Cambaridae ,arose from an ancestor of the Astacidae during the Cenozoic ( Crandall and De Grave, 2017 ;
Grandjean et al. ,2017
; Wolf et al. , 2019). Fossil evidence of
Pacifastacus Bott, 1950
from the Miocene (5–23 MYA) and Pliocene (2.6–5 MYA) has been found in Idaho , USA ( Cope, 1871 ), while fossil material corresponding to European Astacidae and extant species ranges from the Late Jurassic to Pliocene ( Bell, 1863 ;
Feldman et al. ,2011
;
Toon et al. , 2010
; Van Straelen, 1928 ; Via, 1971 ). Fossil evidence is consistent with recent molecular analsses. Of the five extant continents, Astacidae todas occur in both the European and Pacific drainages of North America, Cambaridae are found on the Atlantic side of North and Central America, and Cambaroididae thrive in far eastern Asia. Parastacidae are present in South America, Australia , New Zealand , New Guinea , and Madagascar ( Fig. 26 ).

